Sammy D. (jln2@cec2.wustl.edu) wrote:
: In article <sburnapCCBwC8.Lw6@netcom.com> sburnap@netcom.com (Steven Burnap) writes:
: >Robert I. Eachus (eachus@spectre.mitre.org) wrote:
: >:    Bingo!  The only security associated with most ATM and credit cards
: >: is a dependance on the stupidity of the average crook.  At least in
: >: this country the banks understand that without a picture you get
: >: nowhere in court.  (For international readers, most US ATMs have video
: >: cameras attached.  Some are actually connected to a recorder.)
: >
: >I used to work for a company that did credit authorization
: >software and in doing so, got to play with a mag-strip reader.
: >My ATM card had no PIN, nor did it have any unexplainable numbers, just card
: >number, an expiration date and a name, same as a credit card.

: Yes, and once you've typed everything into the ATM, it encrypts a
: packet containg the card number, your PIN and your request, sends it
: the the server and gets back an encrypted packet saying either
: "dispense the funds" or "get lost, deadbeat".  By the way, a few months
: back some bozos here in St. Louis stole an ATM machine using a stolen
: tow truck.  That night, the local news had the picures from the video
: camera showing excellent closeups of the thieves wrapping chains around
: the ATM, etc.

What I really found facinating about working  with credit authorization
software is that transmissions to and from credit authorization
agencies are *not* encrypted.  Anyone with the right documentation, phone
number, and a dumb terminal can check credit limits.

Steve
